properties.DevelopmentDescription: PROTECTED STRUCTURE: For revisions to previously approved planning permission ref no. 2669/11 (this being a modification of the development permitted under planning register ref: 3726/09) for development on a site measuring 1.24 ha at Orwell Park, Rathgar, Dublin 6 forming part of St. Joseph's retirement and residential centre at nos 47-53 Orwell Park and Darty House, Orwell Park, Dublin 6. Darty House is a protected structure. The development will consist of minor site layout modifications including the following; (a) alterations to 2 no. Detached Type Houses (Unit No. 01A and Unit No. 10B) amending the house width minor building level adjustments, revisions to fenestration of gable and rear elevations and rear elevation finishes (b) minor alterations to 16 no. Semi-Detached Type Houses (Unit No. 02A - 09A, 11B-188) including minor building level adjustments, revisions to rear elevation fenestration and revisions to rear and side elevation finishes no amendments to the granted site access are proposed as part of this planning application.

The development will consist of the change of use of the existing vacant retail unit (212sqm) to a cafe with associated kitchen. The works will also include the erection of timber cladding at the entrance area, signage and provision of outdoor seating to Fumbally Lane.

A. Attic conversion incorporating dormer extension to side and rear.
B. All associated site works.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: The proposed development comprises: (i) demolition of the existing modern single storey return (17sq.m) and construction of a new return to the rear (17sq.m); (ii) construction of a new lift shaft to the rear providing access to all floors (11sq.m); (iii) re-ordering alteration and refurbishment of the interior of the building to facilitate the operation of the Dublin Central Mission and Abbey Street Methodist Church, including restoration of a number of original features, removal of a number of modern interventions and removal of some original fabric. Alteration and refurbishment works to the existing building include the restoration of an apse to the main sacred space; the restoration of original fenestration at top floor level; and the removal of the stage and gallery from the upper level multi-purpose hall. The works also include provision of new fire compartmentation new fire escape stairs meeting and office spaces; ground floor reception/social area (including the room); new toilet accommodation; the installation of roof-lights general upgrading sundry repairs, alterations and renewals; upgrading of services, including installation of solar panels to the south-facing roof slope, all associated site and drainage works.

The proposed enlargement of the existing two storey elderly nursing care facility, known as Beneavin Lodge, will increase total bed numbers by 93 residents and upgrade day, activity space and staff rest and training provision to meet latest Nursing Home Care Standards as set out under HIQA guidelines. The proposal will include a third storey  to the section of the building facing onto Beneavin Road, with an additional two storeys on the rear elevation facing the school playing fields to match the adjacent facility at Beneavin House. Block 2: Amendment of permitted ground to fifth floor levels to include a reduction in retail floorspace by 18sq.m and a reduction in office floorspace by 47 sq.m at ground floor level. For a residential development. The development will consist of a residential development of 86 no. dwellings comprising a total of 52 no. apartments (one and two bedroom) in two no. blocks; 33 no. houses (two, three and four bedroom) and the extension and refurbishment of the existing gate Lodge. The apartments are arranged in two blocks located to the south (rear)  of50283 the site and the houses are located on the balance of the site. Apartment Block 1 is 5 storey over basement in height (3,310sqm gross floor space), providing 35 no. units (10 no. one bedroom and 25 no. two bedroom units) with balconies on all elevations. Apartments Block 2 is part 5, part 6 storeys in height (1,687sqm gross floor space), providing 17 no. two bedroom units, with balconies on all elevations and a roof terrace at fifth floor level. A total of 33 no. new houses comprising a mix of two and three storeys in height in terrace, semi-detached and detached format are proposed. The 33 no. new houses comprise 7 no. two bedroom dwellings (Type F); 13 no. three bedroom dwellings (Types B,B1 and C); and 13 no. four bedroom dwellings (types A,D,E and E1) in terrace; semi-detached and detached form. The three and four bedroom townhouses (Types A to E) are located centrally in the site; adjoining the established two storey, terraced dwellings on Rosemount Road and range in size from approximately 109sqm to 170sqm gross floor area. Two bedroom houses (Type F) are located in a terrace to the north of the site along the principal access road and comprise 91sqm gross floor area (each with external terrace at first floor level on western elevation). The proposed development provides for extension and refurbishment of the existing two bedroom Gate Lodge fronting onto the North Circular Road. The Gate Lodge will be extended to the South and will comprise a two bedroom property (increase in total gross floor area from 67sqm to 83.5sqm). Vehicular and pedestrian access is proposed via an internal access road from the existing access onto the North Circular Road; 47 no. car parking spaces are provided at basement level of apartment Block 1 and 46 no. spaces are provided at surface level for house units and visitor parking. A total of 52 no. bicycle parking spaces are provided at surface level. The proposed development also provides for ESB substation; bin stores; landscaping, site lighting and boundary treatments and all associated site and development works.

Development of a site of 0.1635 ha.  Kestrel House, a corner building, forms part of a larger existing commercial block, adjacent to Marine House at Clanwilliam Place and abutting Osprey House on Grand Canal Street Lower, Dublin 2.
The development will consist of the demolition of the existing 4 storey over basement level building (1,719sq.m.), whilst retaining the staircase to the west side of the building (that currently serves both the existing Kestrel House and Osprey House, which will continue to serve Osprey House after redevelopment (39sq.m.) and some columns within the basement.
The development will also consist of the construction of a seven storey over basement level building (with a screened plant area at rooftop level) with a total gross floor space of 6,427 sq.m., including a basement level of 1,002 sq.m. gross floor space.
The proposal also includes the provision of: 13 no. car parking spaces at basement and ground level; 67 no. bicycle parking spaces at basement level; timber decked terraces at sixth level; green roof; ancillary plant, refuse, storage and service areas at basement level; and an electricity substation and switch room at ground level.  Vehicular access to the site will be from the existing access on Love Lane, with pedestrian access from Clanwilliam Place and Lower Grand Canal Street.  The proposed development also includes boundary treatments, amendment to the existing building lines, hard and soft landscaping and all associated site development works above and below ground including changes in level and the provision of a courtyard area at basement level.

We the Central Bank of Ireland intend to apply for full planning permission for development at this site, Office Building 1 located at the junction of North Wall Quay and New Wapping Street , Dublin 1, with a site area of 1.0214 hectares.

The development will consist of amendments to previously approved planning permission Reg. Ref.: 4964/08 and ABP Reference PL29N.232580. The proposed development comprises amendments to the previously approved office scheme as follows.

- Provision of a new vehicular access with associated flood control measures to two levels of basement from New Wapping Street, in lieu of permitted access from Castleforbes Road. As a consequence it is proposed to omit the part of the east-west route as previously permitted from Castleforbes Road to the site boundary of Office building 1 and permission is sought for the occupation of the building on completion of the proposed new access from New Wapping Street in lieu of Condition Nos. 2, 6 and 9 of ABP Reference PL29N.232580.

-Reconfiguration of the car park, bicycle park, plant rooms and storage facilities to provide 97 no. car parking spaces in lieu of 70 approved car parking spaces located at basement level -2. Provision of 20 no. motorbike parking spaces at basement level -2. Provision of 436 sq. meters of office support space at basement level -2.

-Provide new loading/service bay at basement level -1 with access from New Wapping Street. Reconfiguration of permitted basement layouts to provide for 290 bicycle parking spaces and shower facilities (201 sq.m) at basement level -1. Provision of 1865 sq. metres of office support space at basement level -1 with associated roof lights at the podium at ground floor level.

-Reconfiguration of permitted basement layouts and provision of additional plant and storage areas at basement level -1 and -2. Internal amendments to existing layouts at basement level -1 and -2 to provide an auditorium.

-Change of use of previously permitted exhibition area at ground floor level to be incorporated into approved staff cafe/restaurant.

-Change of use of retail banking hall at ground floor level to public coin exchange / exhibition area at the corner of North Wall Quay and New Wapping Street.

-Revised external hard and soft landscaping works to the podium (including an increase in height of 350 ml of part of podium) including that part of the east-west route from New Wapping Street up to the site boundary of Building 1 and temporary edge treatment to north and east site boundaries to include crash barrier 0.6 metres in height & screen 2.1 metres in height.

-Internal amendments to include omission of part of North East WC core from ground to 7th floor level and omission of north eastern accommodation staircase from 2nd to 7th floor level to provide additional office floorspace.

-Revised services infrastructure from New Wapping Street and additional substation switch room on the eastern elevation at ground floor level.

-Amendments to permitted foul and storm water drainage arrangements to the building.

-The development also includes all internal and external ancillary amendments, site development works and ancillary works as per the planning application drawings.

The completed building will have a total gross floor of approximately 28849 sqm, with 8 storeys over two levels of basement and will have a maximum height of 40831 metres as previously permitted under ABP Reference PL29N.232580.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: For an extensive programme of conservation works at the fire damaged St. Catherine's Church. The proposed works consist of the repair, conservation and restoration of the fire and smoke damaged interiors of the Church. The work will also include the removal and replacement of the following; existing artificial slate roof finish; approximately 80% of the fire damaged ceiling boards, heat damaged vinyl floor coverings; high level clerestorey windows and the leaded Cathedral glass windows at the west end; together with all fire damaged existing building services and internal surface decorations. The badly fire damaged Telford organ, the stations of the cross, the original timber confessionals and all of the stained glass windows are to be removed for full restoration in specialist conservation studios, prior to their reinstatement in the church. All loose furniture and fixtures are to be removed and sorted to protect from damage, for restoration and to facilitate work.

The development will consist/consists of: provision of
New oil terminal, Topaz Terminal No.3, Promenade Road, Dublin Port, Dublin 3, bounded to the South by Tolka Quay Road, to the West by TOP Yard 2 and to the East by an access lane. On completion of same demolish the existing terminal i.e. of - Topaz Terminal No. 1, Alexandra Road, Dublin Port, Dublin 1 which is bounded to the North by Tolka Quay Road, to the South by Alexandra Road and to the West by No. 1 Branch Road North; and - Topaz (Fareplay) Terminal No. 2, Promenade Road, Dublin Port, Dublin 3 which is bounded to the East by No. 2 North Road extension, and to the North by Promenade Road; according to the following phases.
Phase 1: Works at the new Topaz Terminal No.3. Demolition of existing buildings etc. and removal of equipment. The construction of new oil storage tanks with impervious bunding/tertiary containment to a total storage capacity of 59,986m3. There will be tertiary containment for each bund; and 2 no. petrol interceptors; a three (3) storey building consisting of a 2 storey office block on top of a ground floor fire fighting facilities / car parking area. A single storey building with electrical room, MCC room, laboratory, store room. Ground profile to accommodate truck turning & loading yard & truck gantry; car parking; fire fighting facilities including single storey pump house; fire foam tank; pipe bridge; and pipelines; perimeter security fence & gate; CCTV security system; electrical services; overall site lighting; oil pipelines and associated fittings; ancillary development. The development will be a Sevesco Upper Tier Site and comes within the meaning of part 11 of the planning regulations. Revised access to the site is from the North by the Promenade Road entrance and egress is to the east along the existing fire lane.
Phase 2: Following completion proof testing of the new Terminal the existing Topaz Terminal No. 1 and Topaz (Fareplay) Terminal No. 2 will be demolished. The works will comprise of the demolition of Topaz Terminal No. 1 and of Topaz (Fareplay) Terminal No. 2 i.e. removing all tanks, buildings, services and equipment off site from both Terminals except the ESB substation located on Topaz Terminal No. 1. Leaving these sites totally demolished with perimeter walls/fencing left in situ. These are SEVESCO sites. An EIS will be submitted to the Planning Authority with the planning application and the EIS will be available for inspection or purchase at a fee not exceeding the reasonable cost of making a copy, during office hours at the offices of Dublin City Council.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: Permission for development on a site of c 0.0325 hectares at 26-27 Eden Quay, Dublin 1, which incorporates the former Mercantile Marine Office and is a Protected Structure (Ref No. 2492) as modified under granted planning permission 4380/06. The site is bounded to the east by Nos. 28 to 33 Eden Quay and Liberty Hall; to the west by Nos. 15 to 25 Eden Quay; to the south by Eden Quay and the river Liffey and to the north by Abbey Street Old. The development will consist of modifications to the existing protected structure including the change of use from office to retail at ground floor and the erection of a new 4 storey structure to the rear, interconnected with the existing building and includes a retail unit at ground floor level and office use to the floors above. The retail unit extends through from Eden Quay to Abbey Street Old. The total floor area of the proposed development is 1073msq of which 537msq is additional floor area with 536msq being retained floor area. Works to the protected structure include modifications to the existing Eden Quay Elevation to include lowering of the existing ground floor window sill height replicating the stone / window jamb detailing, minor repairs and pointing of stonework, refurbishment / replacement of existing timber windows. Level access is provided to the proposed retail unit by locally adjusting a portion of the floor including modifications to the existing entrance doors to Eden Quay; the brickwork finish to the rear elevation is to be reinstated; the existing basement (31msq) is to be infilled and retained and the limited removal of internal walls, windows, doors to facilitate connection to the new building. Other alterations to the existing building include the retention and infill of 4 no. internal doors; the removal of infill and 2 no. rearwindows; upgrading of existing pipework and electrics; the retention, restoration of fireplace surrounds and mantelpieces, doors, windows, architraves, plasterwork and cornicing; construction of new partition walls, stairs, doors and sanitary fittings; the upgrading of the timber floors, doors and internal glazing to meet fire safety standards. The additional floor area consists of open plan offices on the first, second and third floors connecting into the existing building across an internal atrium between the new and existing building. The additional floor area at ground floor includes the retail unit and separate access to the new vertical circulation of the offices. The elevation to Abbey Street Old will be partly set back at first floor and fully set back at third floor to form terraces at both levels.

The development of the Public Realm and Site Infrastructure provides for all associated site works to facilitate the anticipated development of the Grangegorman Planning Scheme 2012 to include: 
- A general excavation and profiling of the topography to created landscape features including the "HaHa" Feature. 
- Landscaping works to include the retention of existing trees, planting of new trees and the removal of certain trees within the site and in compliance with the Grangegorman Planning scheme 2012. 
- A Network of paved circulation (suitable for vehicular, bicycle and pedestrian traffic) with security access control devices, including bollards and gates, loading bays for delivery, maintenance and emergency vehicles, disabled car parking spaces (43 no.), bicycle parking spaces ( 1150 no,) and provide access to future car parking (which will be subject of separate applications for planning permission). 
- A section of public thoroughfare of Grangegorman Upper and Grangegorman Lower is included within the site and is subject to development comprising realignment and resurfacing incorporating traffic calming platforms, provision for a taxi rank, coach parking, disabled parking and loading bays that require the removal of existing pay and display parking, new pavement, street lighting, tree planting and street furniture.
- 2 no separate grassed playing fields with associated floodlighting, fencing and netting and an all-weather surface multisport pitch and court area with associated floodlighting, fencing and netting. 
- Demolition and alterations to the existing boundary wall which is a Protected structure to provide new entrance arrangements at Morning Star Avenue, Fitzwilliam Place North, Along Grangegorman Upper and Grangegorman Lower, at Fingal Place and along North Circular Road and to extinguish existing entrances to No's 226, 228 and 230 North Circular Road, Dublin 7 and No's 1,2,3,4 and 5 Orchard View, Grangegorman, Dublin 7.
- Associated site infrastructure works for utilities distribution to include new communications, electricity, gas and potable water connections to existing utilities mains,  
- Storm water and foul water drainage systems incorporating attenuation measures and below ground grey water storage. 
- Indicative signage appropriate for wayfinding and the identification of places within the site. 
- Public Realm lighting and security stations. 
- General public Realm fittings and furniture to include water features, seating, canopy shelters. 
- The provision of 3 no Play areas. 
For clarity the application includes the demolition and alteration of defined sections of the boundary wall of the former St. Brendan's Hospital, which is a protected Structure to form new gateways in compliance with the Grangegorman Planning Scheme 2012, The SDZ also includes an additional 10 No. Protected Structures - The Top House, The Laundry Building, The Mortuary, The Former Female House, The Male Infirmary, The Roman Catholic Chapel, The Female Infirmary, The Church of Ireland Chapel, The Clock Tower building and The Lower House (works to which will be the subject of separate application for planning permission).
An Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) has been prepared in respect of this planning application and will be submitted to Dublin City Council with this application.

Permission for the development of 208 No. dwellings, a creche (c.230 sq.m. in Gross Floor Area plus associated outdoor playing area) and two 5-a-side playing pitches at lands located towards the centre of the overall Pelletstown Strategic Development and Regeneration Area at Ashtown Dublin 15. The proposed development represents Phase 3 for Castlethorn and comprises of 15 No. 4-bed houses (9No. 2-storey detached and 6No. 3-storey terraced), 131No. 3-bed houses in a range of house types (2No. detached, 14No. semi-detached, 40No. end of terrace and 75No. mid-terrace houses; all two-storey dwellings, 78No. of which are applied for with the option of providing a single storey rear extension and 65No. with the option also of a fourth bedroom at attic level to be served by a dormer window at the front), 36No. duplexes (18No. 3-bed own door units over ground and first floor with rear gardens and 18No. 2-bed units over second and third floor level with a balcony/terrace) 26No. apartments (18No. 1-bed and 8No. 2-bed each served by a balcony / terrace), all served by a total of 274No. residential car parking spaces (224No. surface spaces predominantly banked and 50No. garage spaces), 2No. creche staff car parking spaces and 17No. visitor car parking spaces associated with the playing pitches as well as 62No. bicycle parking spaces provided for the proposed apartments and duplexes and located in 2No. bicycle stores adjacent to the apartment blocks. The proposed houses range from c. 105 sq.m. to c. 155sq.m. in Gross Floor Area with a maximum height to ridge / parapet level ranging from c. 7.6 metres to c. 9.6 metres. The duplexes range from c. 19sq.m. to c. 112 sq.m. laid out in 3No. 4-storey curved terraces, with a maximum parapet height of c. 14.3 metres, located along the southern edge of the site formally addressing the eastern half of the existing Crescent Park. The apartments range from c. 55sq.m. to c. 89 sq.m. located in two 5-storey point blocks with a maximum parapet height of c. 17.7 metres at either end of the duplex terraces and one 4-storey apartment block in the southeast corner of the site, with a maximum parapet height of c. 14.7 metres, incorporating the creche at ground floor level. The development would contain c.1.04 Ha of public open space comprising of two landscaped pocket parks, one centred in the northern and the other in the southern part of the site at c. 1005 sq.m and c. 1286 sq.m in area, respectively, plus the two playing pitches and surrounding circulation space including perimeter planting in an area comprising c. 8089sq.m. situated to the northwest of the site in addition to incidental areas of open space / setbacks. The proposed scheme has direct frontage to and is served by Royal Canal Avenue connecting east towards Royal Canal Park and west towards Rathborne. The western perimeter road on-site including spur to River Road and the east/west road bisecting the site have been built in accordance with Planning Reg. Ref. 4289/00 as completed. The eastern and northern perimeter roads were built in accordance with an otherwise non-implemented permission Reg. Ref. 6061/04 and are thus applied for now RETENTION and completion of these works. The proposal includes all ancillary site works and services including hard and soft landscaping, boundary treatment, ESB substations and refuse stores on a site of c. 5.8 Ha bounded generally by the River Road and Tolka Valley Park  to the north, Crescent Park and Royal Canal Avenue to the south, undeveloped lands and Royal Canal Park to the east and the Pelletstown House site and Rathborne to the west, at Ashtown, Dublin 15.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: Development at the Dominican Campus, Muckross Park, Marlborough Road, Dublin 4. It is proposed to demolish part of the currently vacant former four storey secondary school building (1548sq. metres in extent) and redundant outhouses attached to the convent and convert this area into a landscaped garden. Following this demolition a new elevation including new windows will be constructed on the rear elevation of the adjoining building now exposed. This building was previously approved as 12 residential units (Register Reference 2592/12). It is proposed to provide a new entrance/porch and electricity meter room on this newly exposed elevation. Parking spaces are to be provided adjacent to the landscaped garden. Permission is also sought for a new roof treatment to incorporate fixtures required to comply with Fire and Building Regulations. It is not part of this application but it is also proposed (as required by an earlier permission) to remove all three adjoining pre-fabricated classroom blocks and restore this area to grass. Muckross House is a protected structure and the redundant former school buildings to be demolished, are within the curtilage of the Protected Structure. The works are intended to improve the setting of the Protected Structure.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE -Development at this sitewithin the over all Grangegorman Strategic Development zone (SDZ),of approx. 28.69 hectares. The specific site of the proposed development comprises approx. 0.72 hectares and is located on the western side of Grangegorman Lower bounded by HSE facilities to the north,  Grangegorman Development Agency offices to the south, HSE facilities to the east and playing fields to the west at the former St. Brendan's Hospital.
The development will consist of demolition works, new extensions, material alterations, and change of use from healthcare use to education use to Structure No. 08 of c. 3,808sqm (3 storeys) known as 'The Top House' (Protected Structure Ref. No. 3282) as follows:- the provision of a double height entrance lobby to the building on southern elevation of c. 53sqm;  a proposed covered external yard to the north side of the building (c. 102sqm);  the demolition of a boiler house of 17sqm at ground floor level;  resulting in a structure of c. 3,946sqm for educational use   (1,803sqm at ground floor, 1,331sqm at first floor and 812sqm at second floor).
The proposed material alterations to Structure 08 will consist of internal alterations, which entails the removal of existing partitions, the provision of new internal partitions, the replacement of defective ceilings, the upgrade of corridors, stairs and floors to improve the fire performance of the structure , the provision of new door openings in the existing structure, the provision of new floor finishes, the provision of new mechanical and electrical services, the provision of new toilet facilities, the refurbishment of existing windows, the refurbishment and repairs to the roof and roof structure, the provision of new glazed rooflights over the central stairs in the western wing, the reinstatement of the original oval floor voids at first and second floor levels in the western wing and the repointing of the stonework. 
Permission is also sought for the provision of 6 no. car parking spaces as well as 54 no. cycle spaces, and all site development works and drainage works to connect to Dublin City Council planning reference 3373/12.  The development will take place entirely within the boundaries of the Grangegorman Strategic Development Zone.
